end information transport for DoW operations to the warfighters and the Combatant Commanders via a robust Command, Control, Communications, Computers and
Intelligence information long-haul transport infrastructure. The DISN, seamlessly spanning the full spectrum from terrestrial to space and strategic to tactical domains,
provides the interoperable telecommunications connectivity required to plan, implement, and support all operational missions, anytime. DISN services reach the edge
of the communications network; the warfighter can access them worldwide. Continual enhancement of the DISN is needed to provide optimal network resources to the
warfighter.

The Defense Red Switch Network (DRSN) is a global, secure voice service providing the President, the Secretary of War, the Joint Chiefs of Staff, the Combatant
Commands (COCOMs) and selected agencies with Nuclear Command, Control, and Communications (NC3) secure voice and video conferencing capabilities and
higher classification levels. The DRSN consists of Military Department and Agency-owned secure voice switches connected by a DISA provided transport backbone.

The RDT&E funding supports the following efforts:

DISN Networking - Tech Refresh (TR) (formally known as Next Generation Networking Technologies): Provides engineering technical expertise to update the global
network with the latest technologies.

DRSN Peripheral and Component Re-Design and MLSV2: Supports Peripheral and Component Re-Design to continue interoperability between DRSN and its operators.
This capability is not commercially available and satisfies unique military requirements for multi-level secure voice services and conferencing capabilities.

Additionally, RDT&E funding supports the development, testing, and fielding of a prototype of the modern Multi-Level Secure Voice and Video (MLSV2) conference
capability. The MLSV2 prototype effort will modernize voice, video and chat conferencing capability providing a flexible and interoperable capability through
standardization of protocols and interfaces as well as orchestration between hardware (HW) and software (SW). The MLSV2 initiative will show future possibilities for
classified conferencing at three classification levels with the same system.

DoW Mobility: The virtual/zero desktop infrastructure and zero-sign on experience will enable the warfighter to access mobile device applications by entering credentials
once. The warfighter will then be automatically verified as he or she accesses additional applications. Additionally, it supports the continued evolution and expansion
of Unified Endpoint Management (UEM) Capabilities for
mobility within the Department. The Unified Endpoint Management Capabilities are a class of
software tools that provide a single management interface for mobile devices, enhancing user experience for the warfighter and COCOMs. The Mobility program is also
expanding research on Derived Credential capabilities, which allows for the automation of the operations, administration, maintenance, and provisioning functions of
and classified mobile endpoints.$$, $$The Defense Information Systems Network (DISN) RDT&E Funding supports the following:

DISN Networking: TR (formally known as Next Generation Networking Technologies): Provides engineering technical expertise to update the global network with
the latest technologies. These new technologies provide protected and assured services for critical global, all theater support to the warfighter as well as other
DoW and federal customers that consume services from the Defense Information Systems Network (DISN). Specific technical focus is on assured, dynamic global
communications networks that can operate under various adversarial threat and risk conditions. Other RDT&E investments are made in ensuring operational and
network operating systems that instrument and automate the operations, administration, maintenance, and provisioning functions creating a single DISN-wide view for
network managers and operators.

DRSN: Supports Peripheral and Component Re-Design between DRSN and its operators. The efforts within this program satisfy unique military requirements for multi-
level secure voice services and conferencing capabilities in support of the Defense Red Switch Network (DRSN), a critical component of the National Military Command
System (NMCS). Commercial equipment is not certified by the NSA to perform necessary encryption requirements of DRSN and Secure Voice Conferencing.
Additionally, RDT&E funding supports the development, testing, and fielding of a prototype of the modern Multi-Level Secure Voice and Video (MLSV2) conference
capability. The MLSV2 effort will provide a modern, flexible, and interoperable voice, video, and chat conferencing capability through standard protocols, interfaces, and
hardware (HW) and software (SW) orchestration. MLSV2 will permit conferencing at three classification levels with one system.

DoW Mobility: Mobility is leading the research, development, and deployment of Enterprise Controlled Unclassified Information (CUI) and classified mobile technologies.
The goal of this effort is to increase information sharing and use of secure mobile devices across the global DoW. The continued evolution and expansion of mobility
capabilities will revolutionize the way Combatant Commands, Services, and Agencies work by enabling on-demand access to services and information anytime,
anywhere.

B. Accomplishments/Planned Programs ($ in Millions)                                                                                      FY 2025           FY 2026     FY 2027
Title: DISN Networking - TR (formally known as Next Generation Networking Technologies)                                                      5.198             4.764       4.844
Description: DISN Networking - TR (formally known as Next Generation Networking Technologies): Provides technical
engineering expertise to develop, design and implement solutions to ensure technical superiority and mission readiness of
the DISN, leverage software-based control to rapidly enable network automation, develop critical technologies needed for
programmable global network backbone at speeds in excess of 400/800 gigabits per second (gbps).

                                                                               - DCS

B. Accomplishments/Planned Programs ($ in Millions)                                                                                 FY 2025    FY 2026      FY 2027
FY 2026 Plans:
• Continue technical evolution of global backbone, supporting development and deployment of several prototype efforts and next
generation of capabilities in theater.
• Develop software solutions to support lab automation and research on network data science, high speed network telemetry and
next generation backbone.
FY 2027 Plans:
• Continue the technical evolution of the global backbone through the development of secure network architectures, prototyping
and evaluation of new DISN services and service delivery models, and the insertion of transformational open source and
commercial products into the DISN.
• Accelerate the DISN service delivery model through new and enhanced proof-of-concept testing methodologies.
• Evaluation and development of transformational network tools supporting digital engineering concepts aiding in network planning
and provisioning automation.
FY 2026 to FY 2027 Increase/Decrease Statement:
The increase of +$0.080 million from FY 2026 to FY 2027 is due to labor and hardware cost increase.
Title: DRSN Peripheral and Component Re-Design and MLSV2                                                                              38.610      29.851         1.706
Description: DRSN: Supports Peripheral and Component Re-Design between DRSN and its operators. The effort satisfies
unique military requirements for multi-level secure voice services and conferencing capabilities in support of the Defense Red
Switch Network, a critical component of the National Military Command System (NMCS). Commercial equipment is not certified by
the NSA to perform necessary encryption requirements of DRSN and Secure Voice Conferencing.
Additionally, RDT&E funding supports the development, testing, and fielding of a prototype of the modern Multi-Level Secure
Voice and Video (MLSV2) conference capability, which will address the future of the DRSN, whether to modernize or replace it.
The MLSV2 effort will provide the modern, flexible, and interoperable voice, video, and chat conferencing capability for both the
tactical and strategic communities, through stands protocols, interfaces, and hardware (HW) and software (SW) orchestration. It
permits three levels of classified conferencing in one system.

FY 2026 Plans:
• Complete integration of the MLSV2 prototype. MLSV2 must be available at nine nodes with three classification levels. DISA will
integrate the MLSV2 prototype with existing communications networks in three environments.
• Develop security operations functions to protect MLSV2. DISA will manage the security of the prototype in three environments
and must invest in the appropriate security.
• Create the capacity to provide Tier I, II, and II support for MLSV2 users.

                                                                              - DCS

B. Accomplishments/Planned Programs ($ in Millions)                                                                               FY 2025    FY 2026      FY 2027
• Achieve MLSV2 Initial Operating Capability in FY 2026 Q4. DISA will deploy the MLSV2 prototype in three Operational
Environments as needed for our partners.
• Test three classification levels with three operational nodes.
• Complete Discovery Phase for Development Project.
FY 2027 Plans:
DRSN: Begin ECTOCRYP Black development project. ECTOCRYP Black is a device that provides high-capacity, secure voice
encryption for classified communications up to the Top-Secret level. (ECD: 30 Sep 2028).
FY 2026 to FY 2027 Increase/Decrease Statement:
The decrease of -$28.145 million from FY 2026 to FY 2027 is a result of completion of MLSV2 RDT&E activities and shift to
sustainment.
Title: Mobility                                                                                                                      3.921       3.851         3.958
Description: The Mobility Program delivers secure, enterprise-level mobile capabilities that enable the Department of War (DoW)
to operate with speed, resilience, and global reach. The program provides integrated, end-to-end mobile solutions that allow
DoW civilians, military personnel, and mission partners to securely access unclassified and classified information and mission
applications from modern mobile devices. These services directly support warfighter readiness, senior leader decision-making,
and distributed operations across Combatant Commands, the Military Services, Defense Agencies, and Field Activities.

The Mobility Program provides the core enterprise infrastructure including mobile device management, identity and access
control, secure mobility gateways, and Zero Trust aligned endpoint protections required to safeguard DoW information in
contested and evolving threat environments. This capability enables mobile users to securely authenticate, communicate,
collaborate, and access operational data regardless of location.

FY 2026 Plans:
• Initiate limited fielding of the new tethered classified mobility solution for select DoW mission partners.
• Investigate and implement enhancements to the Commercial Solutions for Classified (CSfC) architecture, including adoption of
a layered security framework, modernization of components to meet updated NSA cybersecurity standards and emerging protocol
requirements, and expansion of CSfC service options to support rapid deployment of secure classified communications.
• Integrate enterprise mobile data lose prevention (DLP) controls into DISA-managed mobility platforms to prevent unauthorized
data access, transfer, or exfiltration across DoW mobile devices and applications.
• Deploy digital data rights management (DRM) protections enabling granular control of data usage (view, share, forward, copy/
paste, screenshot restrictions) to ensure sensitive information remains protected when acceded on mobile endpoints.

                                                                                - DCS

B. Accomplishments/Planned Programs ($ in Millions)                                                                                 FY 2025       FY 2026       FY 2027
• Conduct operational demonstrations with Combatant Commands and mission partners to validate Cross Domain Mobility (CDM)
capability, alignment with security policies, and interoperability with existing enterprise platforms.
• Conduct 5G mobility pilot assessment to evaluate next-generation wireless technologies.
FY 2027 Plans:
• Conduct technical assessments of mobile text messaging platforms to determine appropriate policy, technical feasibility, and
compliance pathways for retaining, auditing, and securely storing mobile text communications across DoW-managed mobility
platform.
• Assess mobile gateway modernization needs to enable Enterprise Gray adoption at scale, including enhancements to routing,
VPN services, encryption modules, logging, and traffic inspection capabilities required to secure mobile communications across
gray transport channels.
• Pilot deployment of AI-driven mobile threat defense (MTD) to detect anomalous device behavior.
• Deploy advanced application-vetting and threat detection tools integrated with mobile device platforms to strengthen mobile
cybersecurity protections.
• Enhance Commercial Solutions for Classified (CSfC) capabilities by finalizing layered security architecture designs, completing
compliance upgrades with updated NSA security standards, and conducting field tests for rapid deployment toolkits.
FY 2026 to FY 2027 Increase/Decrease Statement:
The increase of +$0.107 million from FY 2026 to FY 2027 reflects the ramp-up of planned activities, including the fielding
of Classified Retransmission Devices (RDs), expansion of Zero Trust integration across unclassified and classified mobility
environments, enhancement of Mobile DLP/DRM, and the continued development of cross-domain and 5G mobility capabilities to
meet growing operational requirements.
