$$, $$08a7c9492a6b3f3caf909e6c9c60e07fa9b8523ae79c7bb5989e99035ee839e4$$, $${"A": "651b68e8fee5b49159ecd3747d3c13be3174097f46d562dd9fbab96d1ccc9159", "C": "d4fdf923ba776b98bda680220afe7660b2fb7f78e25f4cb026ad0b29031d9620", "D": "669498fe5fddbc9ffe879ae4b3fc94935216f535fe513ceca5f4af2b2d3af2c3"}$$::jsonb, $$Budget J-Books/FY27/Remaining/RDTE_SOCOM_PB_2027.pdf$$, 21, $$2026-05-10T04:04:20.593176+00:00$$) ON CONFLICT DO NOTHING;
INSERT INTO public.pe_narratives (pe_id, fiscal_year, mission_description, justification, accomplishments, planned_program, performance_metrics, other_program_funding, raw_text, content_hash, section_hashes, source_pdf, source_page, ingested_at) VALUES ($$0604115C$$, 2027, $$Technology Maturation Initiatives (TMI) demonstrates the utility of non-kinetics for missile defense applications.

 This initiative advances non-kinetic science and technology for missile defense by investing in the following critical areas:
 - Directed energy kill chain acceleration - Increases MDA investment in Directed Energy Demonstrators and Critical Components required for kill chain closure. Projects
 include next-generation advancements in thermal management, electrical storage, power generation, optical sources, and effects assessments.
 - Electronic protection - Provides for testing and demonstration of advanced electronic protection with Missile Defense System radars.
 - Multi-domain directed energy - This accelerates MDA's testing and demonstration of directed energy for missile defense. Projects include concept-of-operations
 refinement, automation, SWaP improvements, and integrated beam director applications.

 To enable the operational use of non-kinetics for missile defense on land, sea, air, or space platforms, SWaP scaling involves targeted advancements in several critical
 areas, including:
 - Increasing electrical- efficiency: Developing next-generation sources which directly reduces waste heat and lessens demands on the platform's power and cooling
 capacity.
 - Advanced thermal management: Researching and maturing lightweight cooling techniques capable of dissipating waste heat from a compact system, a key enabler for
 sustained high-power operations.
 - High-density power systems: Investing in miniaturized, high-density energy storage and power generation to meet the significant electrical demands of a high-power
 weapon system within a constrained volume.
 - Ruggedized beam directors: Engineering compact beam directors that are adaptable to multi-domain environments with minimal weight and footprint for Service
 proliferation.

 The Directed Energy Demonstrator Development project incrementally demonstrates and improves the components required for the acquisition, tracking, and lethality
 kill chain. This effort advances the Technology Readiness Levels (TRLs) of emerging technologies while assessing their performance and potential contributions to the
 Missile Defense System architecture. Through an agile systems engineering cycle, TMI examines, develops, tests, and improves disruptive non-kinetic technologies.
Services, Defense Advanced Research Projects Agency, Department of Energy, Other Government Agencies, and the National Laboratories to mature and conduct
 demonstration/rapid prototype of non-kinetic weapons technology.

 The funds requested in this PE provide both legacy and Global Missile Defense Capability development for the United States, its deployed forces, allies, and partners.
 The capabilities funded by this budget request are complementary to the architecture funded by the Golden Dome Program's separate budget request and together
 fulfill the President's Executive Order 14186. The President's January 27, 2025, Executive Order established a goal of protecting the U.S. citizens, safeguarding critical
 infrastructure, and securing second-strike capability against missile attack from any adversary. This program and budget in addition to the budget requested by the
 Golden Dome Program Office reflects the changes necessary to protect the U.S. against ballistic, hypersonic, cruise, and other advanced missile threats.$$, $$The Directed Energy Demonstrator Development (DEDD) project reduces technology risk and matures critical directed energy technologies to support the Missile
Defense System. This project directly aligns with the Office of the Under Secretary of War for Research and Engineering efforts and provides the foundational data,
components, and advancement required for connected non-kinetic weapon systems. The DEDD project is comprised of two focused efforts.
- Non-Kinetic
- Electronic Protection

 The non-kinetic effort is focused on demonstrating an accelerated directed energy kill chain suitable for ground, air, and space applications, directly supporting the
 Missile Defense Agency. The objective is to mature and integrate the technologies required to acquire, track, and defeat advanced missile threats in all phases-of-flight
 from all military domains. Analytical products and digital environments will enable rapid Concept of Operations (CONOPS) evolutions and Tactics, Techniques, and
 Procedures (TTP) maturation in Wargames, Exercise, and other demonstration events.

 This project will mature next-generation components that enable lethal power levels within a package suitable for eventual weapon system integration. This work
 includes:
 - Kill Chain Demonstration and Lethality: This focuses on maturing the functional elements of the kill chain. It includes developing and testing high-performance tracking
 lasers, detectors, and algorithms to handover to kinetic and non-kinetic systems. As needed, this effort will execute lethality demonstrations using high-power, non-
 kinetic weapons.
 - Enabling SWaP: To ensure the kill chain components can be integrated onto Service platforms. This includes maturing ruggedized, lightweight subsystems (e.g beam
 directors, thermal management, and power systems) capable of handling the demands of a SWaP constrained environment. Success in this area is a prerequisite for
 demonstrating utility in new service platforms.

 The Electronic Protection effort addresses the critical need to ensure that Missile Defense System (MDS) assets, particularly advanced radars, can maintain
 performance and survivability in a modern electronic environment. This project will test and demonstrate advanced electronic protection techniques for MDS radars.

