$$, $$2901a9ee69bef7743130cba3b806393fd61d56166904906d834913f52d3f5369$$, $${"A": "2affdc53cba65ce34b7b9baf90557687052a67391c0381c93d105b4335ee2ebd", "C": "d4fdf923ba776b98bda680220afe7660b2fb7f78e25f4cb026ad0b29031d9620", "D": "2d17abcbaf5213139e96ac98e0ee0f33ae9f39fc50bd18513c030879cbaa3c81"}$$::jsonb, $$Budget J-Books/FY27/Remaining/RDTE_TJS_PB_2027.pdf$$, 59, $$2026-05-10T04:04:21.937511+00:00$$) ON CONFLICT DO NOTHING;
INSERT INTO public.pe_narratives (pe_id, fiscal_year, mission_description, justification, accomplishments, planned_program, performance_metrics, other_program_funding, raw_text, content_hash, section_hashes, source_pdf, source_page, ingested_at) VALUES ($$0204571J$$, 2027, $$The Joint Staff Analytical Support (JSAS) family of programs provide defense analytical support capabilities for the Joint Staff and Combatant Commands (CCMDs).
JSAS encompasses tools and infrastructure required to conduct analyses and formulate results that assist the Chairman in fulfilling his statutory responsibilities.
A primary focus of this analysis is the development of the operational concepts that guide the evolution of the Joint Force. This effort is led by the threat-informed
Joint Warfighting Concept (JWC), an overarching framework that is detailed through subordinate Concepts of Operation (CONOPS) and Concepts of Employment
(CONEMPs). These integrated concepts describe how the force will fight and drive the identification of Concept-Required Capabilities (CRCs). This ensures that the
entire JWC family of concepts provides direct, traceable input to the Joint Force Requirements Process (JFRP), aids senior leader decision-making, and implements
timely, low-cost Joint Force development initiatives.$$, $$The Joint Staff Analytical Support (JSAS) program provides analytic and management support to the Chairman’s Title 10 requirement to develop urgent and long-term
Joint concepts. These threat-based Joint concepts advance Joint force operational effectiveness and enable the introduction and incorporation of new capabilities. The
Joint concepts program supports the Chairman's responsibility to articulate a vision for the future Joint force; address operational problems on a 20-year horizon; identify
Joint force development implications; and identify capabilities required to mitigate and solve future Joint warfighting gaps. The goal is to enable investment decisions
balancing near and long-term risk. Threat-informed Joint concepts drive capability development and promote horizontal integration for force development across the
Services, Combatant Commands, Defense agencies, OSW and Joint Staff. Key deliverables include:

 Joint Operating Environment (JOE) and the Gamechangers report: Developed in partnership with the Defense Intelligence Agency (DIA), these reports describe
 the future security environment and project the implications of change for the Joint Force. The documents describe the circumstances that may alter the security
 environment and explore how the intersection and interaction of these changes might impact the character of war in the future. They provide a framework to think about
 the full range of Joint force missions and how they may evolve over time to support development of threat-based future Joint concepts and CONOPS.

 Joint Warfighting Design 2040 (JWD 2040): Describes the attributes of the future Joint force and identifies areas for Service examination and experimentation. It
 prepares the Joint force for the future character of warfare – as outlined in the Joint Operating Environment – and provides a force design that balances unity of effort
 with Service-specific contributions. JWD 2040 is developed through ongoing collaboration with the Services, Combatant Commands, Defense Agencies, the Intelligence
 Community, industry, academia, and key allies and partners.

 The Joint Warfighting Concept (JWC): The Department of War's overarching vision for how the Joint Force will fight in the future. It provides a threat-informed,
 operational concept for how the U.S. military will operate as a cohesive team across all domains, including land, sea, air, space, and cyberspace. The JWC is designed
 to guide the development of future force structure, capabilities, and doctrine to deter and, if necessary, defeat near-peer adversaries in a high-intensity conflict. This
 concept has been formally incorporated into military doctrine with the publication of Joint Publication 1, Volume 1, Joint Warfighting, and serves as the foundation for
 modernizing the Joint Force.

 Concepts of Operations (CONOPS): Describe how the actions of the Joint force components and supporting organizations, consistent with ideas from Joint concepts,
 are integrated, synchronized, and phased to accomplish a specific mission, war plan or function within the construct of a future scenario. CONOPS support evaluation of
 new ways of operating, future force posture mix, advanced capabilities, and authorities in exercises, wargames, and experiments.

                                                                                                                                  Design
 Concepts of Employment (CONEMPs): A CONEMP is a detailed operational concept that describes how a specific, emerging military capability will be used to
 achieve desired effects and advantages against an adversary. Building upon the broad vision of a Joint Concept or CONOPS, a CONEMP focuses on the tactical and
 operational-level "how," outlining the tasks, command and control relationships, and integration of a new capability within the existing force structure. They are critical
 for exploring the doctrine, organization, training, materiel, leadership and education, personnel, facilities, and policy (DOTMLPF-P) implications of a new technology or
 system before it is widely fielded, ensuring it can be effectively integrated to support the Joint Force.

 Concept-Required Capabilities (CRCs): Concept-Required Capabilities are specific, high-level capability proposals identified during the joint concept development
 process that are deemed essential to executing a concept's central idea. To ensure clarity and analytical rigor, each CRC is constructed using the Task, Purpose,
 Condition, and Standard structure. This framework articulates what the Joint Force must do (Task), why it is necessary (Purpose), the challenging operational
 circumstances in which it must be done (Condition), and the required level of performance (Standard). Once identified and validated, CRCs serve as the direct,
 authoritative input from the joint concept development process into the Joint Force Requirements Process (JFRP), providing the foundation for detailed analysis and
 resourcing decisions.

 Joint Advanced Fires Qualification Course (JAFQ-C): Develop, standup, and execute JAFQ-C as the OCR for an OUSD P&R initiative as a critical task under CJADC2.
 JAFQ-C will deliver qualified specialist for operational-level, all-domain joint fires to address Joint Warfighting Concept issues for CCMDs, JTFs, and Components
 supporting Joint Fires Elements.

